Molecular Crystals

A crystal is a solid composed of certain atomic or molecular building blocks packed up in regular, repeated order. The building block is called the unit cell. The unit cell of a molecular crystal, the subject of this activity, contains one or more molecules, instead of atoms (held together with covalent bonds) or ions (held together with charge). Molecular crystals are very common in our daily life. For example, ice is a molecular crystal, composed of molecules of water. 

The interactions between unit cells in molecular crystals are typically van der Waals interactions or hydrogen bonds that bind the molecules loosely. As a result, molecular crystals are typically softer and have lower melting points than the other types of crystals.

Understanding key characteristics of molecular crystals is important in biotechnology and nanotechnology. Many drugs are purified from solutions into the form of a molecular crystal in order to maintain their stability and safety. The Food and Drug Administration does not approve a new drug without obtaining a specification of its crystal structure. Yet getting many molecules such as proteins into well-shaped crystals so that their structure can be analysed is challenging (but critical) work.


